<!-- показ одной работы -->
	
	<div style="padding-top:3px; font-size: 1.4rem;">This paper is mostly based on the research of Jindra and Walkling (2004) and focused on investigating explanatory variables for the spreads between offer price and the price one day after the announcement of the offer. This spread is called &ldquo;speculation spread&rdquo; by Jindra and Walkling (2004) and it expresses the merger arbitrage risk expected by market participants &ndash; the risk that the deal will be withdrawn and shareholders will not be able to sell their shares for the offer price.Main finding of this paper is the proof of four hypotheses by testing significance and checking robustness of four independent variables. First two variables were introduced and tested on the sample of US domestic deals by Jindra and Walkling (2004) and my contribution consists in testing these variables on the international sample of cross-border transactions.Hypothesis 1: Market participants successfully anticipate merger arbitrage returns in cross-border transactions. Within this hypothesis the variable &ldquo;revision returns&rdquo; was tested on explanation of the speculation spread. Revision returns express the returns from the offer price revision or from the offer withdrawal. In the second case revision return is usually negative. The resulted relation between the revision return and the speculation spread was negatively significant and robust.Hypothesis 2: Market participants do not successfully anticipate the duration of the offer within merger arbitrage in cross-border transactions. Within this hypothesis, the variable &ldquo;duration of the offer&rdquo; was tested. The resulted relation between the duration of the offer and the speculation spread was significant in some models but not robust.Other two variables were implied from the financial and economic logic and introduced by myself. First one is &ldquo;unemployment rate&rdquo;, which became the best proxy for business environment, existence of new opportunities and growth potential in the target country. Hypothesis 3: Higher unemployment rate in the target country increases merger arbitrage risk expected by market participants. Testing of unemployment rate could be possible on the international sample only. This was one of the reasons to collect an international sample for my research. The resulted relation between unemployment rate and the speculation spread was positively significant and robust.The last variable is connected with financing opportunities and soundness of the acquirer. It is a leverage measure, which is very popular in the market community &ndash; Net debt / EBITDA. I tried to capture both the conditions before the announcement and changes if the deal will be completed. Therefore, I calculated &ldquo;new Net debt to EBITDA of the acquirer in the case of the completed deal&rdquo;. Hypothesis 4: The ratio of Net debt to EBITDA of the acquirer in the case of the completed deal given the offer price and share sought is positively related to the merger arbitrage risk expected by market participants. The resulted relation between the new Net debt to EBITDA and the speculation spread was positively significant and robust.</div>
	
	
<!-- показ одной работы END -->

